    <title>Algorithmic Coercion with Faster Pricing</title>
    <updated>2025-07-01T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Zach Y. Brown &amp; Alexander MacKay</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt; NBER Working Papers&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;We examine a model in which one firm uses a pricing algorithm that enables faster pricing and multi-period commitment. We characterize a coercive equilibrium in which the algorithmic firm maximizes its profits subject to the incentive compatibility constraint of its rival. By adopting an algorithm that enables faster pricing and (imperfect) commitment, a firm can unilaterally induce substantially higher equilibrium prices even when its rival maximizes short-run profits and cannot collude. The algorithmic firm can earn profits that exceed its share of collusive profits, and coercive equilibrium outcomes can be worse for consumers than collusive outcomes. We use simulations to show how coercion arises rapidly when the algorithmic firm’s rival uses a simple learning process to set prices. Finally, we examine the implications of algorithm technology for platform design.</content>
